I’d implement it as two pipelines:

1. UI repo CI builds/tests the UI and publishes an immutable container image.
2. Manifests/CD repo receives the image digest and deploys it to the right environment based on branch rules.

The main change from the notes is: remove Docker Compose from CI/CD. Compose can remain for local dev temporarily, but CI should use native GitLab jobs, a pinned CI/dev image, and a production Dockerfile.

⸻

1. Target repo layout

ui-repo/
  Dockerfile
  nginx.conf
  package.json
  package-lock.json | pnpm-lock.yaml
  .gitlab-ci.yml
  ci/
    Dockerfile
    environment.yml          # only if Conda is still needed
    conda-lock.yml           # preferred for deterministic Conda envs

For the CD side:

manifests-repo/
  apps/
    ui/
      base/
        deployment.yaml
        service.yaml
        ingress.yaml
        kustomization.yaml
      overlays/
        dev/
          kustomization.yaml
        staging/
          kustomization.yaml
        prod-high/
          kustomization.yaml

Do not create a low-side prod overlay if the rule is “main deploys nothing on low side.”

⸻

2. Production UI container

Use a multi-stage Dockerfile: build the static UI, then serve it with Nginx.

# Dockerfile
FROM node:20-alpine AS build
WORKDIR /app
COPY package*.json ./
RUN npm ci
COPY . .
RUN npm run build
FROM nginx:1.27-alpine AS runtime
COPY nginx.conf /etc/nginx/conf.d/default.conf
COPY --from=build /app/dist /usr/share/nginx/html
EXPOSE 8080
HEALTHCHECK --interval=30s --timeout=3s \
  CMD wget -qO- http://localhost:8080/healthz || exit 1
CMD ["nginx", "-g", "daemon off;"]

Example nginx.conf for an SPA:

server {
    listen 8080;
    server_name _;
    root /usr/share/nginx/html;
    index index.html;
    location = /healthz {
        access_log off;
        return 200 "ok\n";
    }
    location / {
        try_files $uri $uri/ /index.html;
    }
    gzip on;
    gzip_types text/plain text/css application/json application/javascript text/xml application/xml image/svg+xml;
}

The production image should not contain Conda, dev tooling, test dependencies, or Docker Compose.

⸻

3. CI/dev container

If Tasking UI used Conda to stabilize tooling, keep that pattern only in the CI/dev image.

Example:

# ci/Dockerfile
FROM mambaorg/micromamba:1.5.10
USER root
RUN apt-get update && apt-get install -y \
    git \
    curl \
    ca-certificates \
    build-essential \
    && rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*
COPY ci/environment.yml /tmp/environment.yml
RUN micromamba install -y -n base -f /tmp/environment.yml \
    && micromamba clean -a -y
ENV PATH=/opt/conda/bin:$PATH
ENV CI=true
ENV TZ=UTC
WORKDIR /workspace

Example ci/environment.yml:

name: ui-ci
channels:
  - conda-forge
dependencies:
  - nodejs=20
  - python=3.11
  - pip
  - git

Best practice would be to generate a lock file:

conda-lock -f ci/environment.yml -p linux-64

Then build from the lock file instead of a floating environment. The goal is that local dev, CI, and the GitLab runner all use the same dependency universe.

⸻

4. GitLab CI pipeline

This version does the following:

* Builds/tests using the CI image.
* Builds the production UI image.
* Pushes the image to GitLab Container Registry.
* Emits the immutable image digest.
* Updates the manifests repo only on allowed branches.

stages:
  - test
  - build
  - publish
  - deploy
variables:
  APP_IMAGE: "$CI_REGISTRY_IMAGE/ui"
  CI_IMAGE: "$CI_REGISTRY_IMAGE/ci:stable"
  DOCKERFILE_PATH: "$CI_PROJECT_DIR/Dockerfile"
workflow:
  rules:
    - if: '$CI_COMMIT_BRANCH'
    - if: '$CI_COMMIT_TAG'
default:
  interruptible: true
  retry:
    max: 1
    when:
      - runner_system_failure
      - stuck_or_timeout_failure
test_ui:
  stage: test
  image: "$CI_IMAGE"
  tags:
    - shared-runner
  script:
    - npm ci
    - npm run lint
    - npm run typecheck
    - npm run test:ci
  rules:
    - if: '$CI_COMMIT_BRANCH =~ /^feature\//'
    - if: '$CI_COMMIT_BRANCH == "dev"'
    - if: '$CI_COMMIT_BRANCH =~ /^release\//'
    - if: '$CI_COMMIT_BRANCH == "main"'
build_ui_image:
  stage: build
  image:
    name: gcr.io/kaniko-project/executor:v1.23.2-debug
    entrypoint: [""]
  tags:
    - shared-runner
  script:
    - mkdir -p /kaniko/.docker
    - >
      echo "{\"auths\":{\"$CI_REGISTRY\":{\"username\":\"$CI_REGISTRY_USER\",\"password\":\"$CI_REGISTRY_PASSWORD\"}}}"
      > /kaniko/.docker/config.json
    - >
      /kaniko/executor
      --context "$CI_PROJECT_DIR"
      --dockerfile "$DOCKERFILE_PATH"
      --destination "$APP_IMAGE:$CI_COMMIT_SHA"
      --destination "$APP_IMAGE:$CI_COMMIT_REF_SLUG"
      --digest-file image-digest.txt
    - echo "IMAGE_REF=$APP_IMAGE@$(cat image-digest.txt)" > image.env
  artifacts:
    reports:
      dotenv: image.env
    paths:
      - image-digest.txt
    expire_in: 7 days
  rules:
    - if: '$CI_COMMIT_BRANCH'
deploy_dev:
  stage: deploy
  image: alpine:3.20
  tags:
    - shared-runner
  needs:
    - job: build_ui_image
      artifacts: true
  variables:
    TARGET_ENV: dev
  before_script:
    - apk add --no-cache git yq
    - git config --global user.email "gitlab-ci@example.internal"
    - git config --global user.name "GitLab CI"
  script:
    - git clone "https://oauth2:${MANIFESTS_TOKEN}@${MANIFESTS_REPO_URL}" manifests
    - cd manifests/apps/ui/overlays/dev
    - yq -i '.images[0].newName = strenv(APP_IMAGE) | .images[0].digest = env(IMAGE_REF | split("@")[1])' kustomization.yaml
    - cd ../../../../
    - git add apps/ui/overlays/dev/kustomization.yaml
    - git commit -m "Deploy UI ${CI_COMMIT_SHORT_SHA} to dev"
    - git push origin HEAD:main
  environment:
    name: dev
  rules:
    - if: '$CI_COMMIT_BRANCH =~ /^feature\//'
    - if: '$CI_COMMIT_BRANCH == "dev"'
deploy_staging:
  stage: deploy
  image: alpine:3.20
  tags:
    - shared-runner
  needs:
    - job: build_ui_image
      artifacts: true
  variables:
    TARGET_ENV: staging
  before_script:
    - apk add --no-cache git yq
    - git config --global user.email "gitlab-ci@example.internal"
    - git config --global user.name "GitLab CI"
  script:
    - git clone "https://oauth2:${MANIFESTS_TOKEN}@${MANIFESTS_REPO_URL}" manifests
    - cd manifests/apps/ui/overlays/staging
    - yq -i '.images[0].newName = strenv(APP_IMAGE) | .images[0].digest = env(IMAGE_REF | split("@")[1])' kustomization.yaml
    - cd ../../../../
    - git add apps/ui/overlays/staging/kustomization.yaml
    - git commit -m "Deploy UI ${CI_COMMIT_SHORT_SHA} to staging"
    - git push origin HEAD:main
  environment:
    name: staging
  rules:
    - if: '$CI_COMMIT_BRANCH =~ /^release\//'
deploy_prod_high:
  stage: deploy
  image: alpine:3.20
  tags:
    - shared-runner
  needs:
    - job: build_ui_image
      artifacts: true
  variables:
    TARGET_ENV: prod-high
  before_script:
    - apk add --no-cache git yq
    - git config --global user.email "gitlab-ci@example.internal"
    - git config --global user.name "GitLab CI"
  script:
    - git clone "https://oauth2:${MANIFESTS_TOKEN}@${MANIFESTS_REPO_URL}" manifests
    - cd manifests/apps/ui/overlays/prod-high
    - yq -i '.images[0].newName = strenv(APP_IMAGE) | .images[0].digest = env(IMAGE_REF | split("@")[1])' kustomization.yaml
    - cd ../../../../
    - git add apps/ui/overlays/prod-high/kustomization.yaml
    - git commit -m "Deploy UI ${CI_COMMIT_SHORT_SHA} to prod-high"
    - git push origin HEAD:main
  environment:
    name: prod-high
  rules:
    - if: '$CI_COMMIT_BRANCH == "main" && $SIDE == "high"'
      when: manual

You would define these protected GitLab variables:

MANIFESTS_REPO_URL
MANIFESTS_TOKEN
SIDE                 # high or low

For production, MANIFESTS_TOKEN should be protected and only available on protected branches.

